Recently, I set up and troubleshooted a Docker environment inside WSL (Ubuntu on Windows), focusing on system-level configuration and container runtime reliability. 

🔹 Problem Scope
The initial setup failed due to multiple infrastructure-level issues:
- Docker daemon not starting correctly in WSL (no systemd support)
- iptables / nftables incompatibility affecting Docker bridge networking
- Docker socket permission issues preventing CLI access
- DNS and network resolution issues impacting image pulls from Docker Hub
- Container runtime initialization errors (containerd + networking stack)

🔹 Approach & Debugging
- I systematically diagnosed and resolved issues across multiple layers:
- Configured and validated Docker daemon (dockerd) execution in WSL
- Resolved Linux permission model issues using Docker group management
- Fixed networking stack by switching iptables to legacy mode
- Analyzed Docker and containerd logs to identify runtime failures
- Verified connectivity and stabilized image pulling from registry
- Tested end-to-end container execution workflow

🔹 Outcome
- Fully functional Docker environment running inside WSL
- Successful execution of container lifecycle (pull → run → exit)
- Stable networking and container runtime behavior

🔹 Key Technical Learnings
- Docker architecture: daemon vs CLI separation
- Linux networking (iptables, bridge networks, NAT rules)
- WSL limitations without systemd and their impact on services
- Container runtime internals (containerd, overlayfs)
- Debugging infrastructure issues using system logs and CLI tools
